{
  "How many types of simple machines are there?": "",
  "Six types of simple machines": "",
  "Four types of simple machines": "",
  "Three types of simple machines": "",
  "Eight types of simple machines": "",
  "There are six types of simple machines: lever, wheel and axle, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw. All complex machines are combinations of these six simple machines.": "",
  "What is the main purpose of a simple machine?": "",
  "To create energy from nothing at all": "",
  "To make work easier by changing force or direction": "",
  "To eliminate friction between all surfaces": "",
  "To increase the total amount of work you do": "",
  "Simple machines make work easier by multiplying force, changing the direction of force, or increasing the distance over which force is applied. They do not create energy or reduce the total work needed.": "",
  "Which simple machine is a ramp an example of?": "",
  "A pulley for lifting objects": "",
  "A lever for prying objects up": "",
  "An inclined plane for moving up": "",
  "A wheel and axle for rolling": "",
  "A ramp is an inclined plane, one of the six simple machines. It allows you to move objects upward using less force over a longer distance, instead of lifting straight up with more force.": "",
  "A seesaw is an example of which simple machine?": "",
  "A screw for holding things": "",
  "A wedge for splitting items": "",
  "A pulley for redirecting force": "",
  "A lever with a fulcrum point": "",
  "A seesaw is a lever with the fulcrum (pivot point) in the middle. When one side goes down, the other goes up. Levers can multiply force or change its direction.": "",
  "What does a pulley do?": "",
  "It changes the direction of the applied force": "",
  "It eliminates the need for any force at all": "",
  "It increases the weight of the lifted object": "",
  "It converts heat energy into kinetic energy": "",
  "A single pulley changes the direction of force (pulling down to lift up). Multiple pulleys can also multiply force, allowing you to lift heavy loads with less effort over a longer rope distance.": "",
  "A knife blade is an example of which simple machine?": "",
  "An inclined plane for going up": "",
  "A wedge for cutting or splitting": "",
  "A screw for holding things tight": "",
  "A knife blade is a wedge. It has a thin, angled edge that concentrates force into a small area, making it effective at cutting or splitting materials apart.": "",
  "A screw is actually a modified version of which other simple machine?": "",
  "A lever wrapped around a cylinder": "",
  "A pulley wound in a spiral shape": "",
  "An inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder": "",
  "A wheel and axle stacked vertically": "",
  "A screw is an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder. The threads of the screw are the ramp. Turning the screw moves it forward with great force over a short distance.": "",
  "A steering wheel is an example of which simple machine?": "",
  "A wheel and axle for rotation": "",
  "A pulley for changing direction": "",
  "A wedge for splitting objects": "",
  "A steering wheel is a wheel and axle. The large wheel allows you to apply force over a greater distance (circumference), which is converted to a larger force at the smaller axle.": "",
  "Do simple machines reduce the total amount of work done?": "",
  "Yes, they reduce total work significantly": "",
  "No, they keep total work the same but change force or distance": "",
  "Yes, they eliminate all work completely": "",
  "No, they actually increase total work done": "",
  "Simple machines do not reduce total work. Work = force x distance stays the same. They trade force for distance: less force over a greater distance, or more force over a shorter distance.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT one of the six simple machines?": "",
  "Lever for lifting things up": "",
  "Spring for storing energy here": "",
  "Wedge for splitting materials": "",
  "Pulley for redirecting forces": "",
  "A spring is not one of the six simple machines. The six are: lever, wheel and axle, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw.": "",
  "What is a simple machine?": "",
  "A basic device that changes the magnitude or direction of a force": "",
  "A complex device with many moving parts like gears and motors": "",
  "A machine that creates energy from nothing at all in the world": "",
  "A device that only works when connected to electricity or power": "",
  "A simple machine is a basic mechanical device that changes the magnitude or direction of force. It has few or no moving parts and makes work easier without creating new energy.": "",
  "What is a lever?": "",
  "A rigid bar that rotates around a fixed pivot point": "",
  "A flat surface tilted at an angle to the ground below": "",
  "A rope looped over a wheel to change force direction": "",
  "A thin edge used to split or cut apart materials": "",
  "A lever is a rigid bar that pivots around a fixed point called the fulcrum. By applying force at one end, you can move a load at the other end. Examples include seesaws, crowbars, and scissors.": "",
  "What is an inclined plane?": "",
  "A flat surface set at an angle to move objects to different heights": "",
  "A rope and wheel system used to lift heavy objects straight up": "",
  "A thin edge designed to split or cut through hard materials": "",
  "A bar that pivots around a fixed point to multiply applied force": "",
  "An inclined plane is a flat surface tilted at an angle. It allows you to raise objects to a higher level using less force over a longer distance. Ramps, hills, and slides are inclined planes.": "",
  "What is a pulley?": "",
  "A wheel with a groove for a rope that redirects force": "",
  "A flat ramp used to move objects to a higher level": "",
  "A sharp edge used for cutting or splitting materials": "",
  "A rotating bar used to turn and move heavy objects": "",
  "A pulley is a wheel with a groove around it for a rope or cable. A single pulley changes the direction of force. Multiple pulleys (block and tackle) can also multiply force.": "",
  "What is a wedge?": "",
  "A thick, V-shaped tool that splits or separates objects": "",
  "A circular wheel used to change force direction with rope": "",
  "A flat ramp tilted at an angle for moving objects up": "",
  "A rod that pivots around a fulcrum point for lifting": "",
  "A wedge is a simple machine shaped like two inclined planes joined together. It converts a force applied to its blunt end into forces that push outward, splitting or cutting. Axes and knives are wedges.": "",
  "What is a wheel and axle?": "",
  "A large wheel attached to a smaller cylinder that rotate together": "",
  "A rope looped over a grooved wheel for lifting heavy objects": "",
  "A rigid bar that pivots around a fixed fulcrum for leverage": "",
  "A flat surface tilted at an angle for moving objects upward": "",
  "A wheel and axle consists of a larger wheel attached to a smaller cylinder (axle) that rotate together. Force applied to the wheel is multiplied at the axle. Doorknobs and screwdrivers are examples.": "",
  "What is a screw?": "",
  "An inclined plane wrapped in a spiral around a cylinder": "",
  "A flat ramp placed at an angle against a wall or step": "",
  "A wheel with a groove used for lifting heavy objects": "",
  "A sharp edge used for cutting through hard materials": "",
  "A screw is an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder. The spiral threads convert rotational force into linear force. Screws can hold things together (wood screws) or lift things (jar lids, car jacks).": "",
  "What does 'effort force' mean?": "",
  "The force you apply to a simple machine to do work": "",
  "The weight of the object being moved by the machine": "",
  "The friction that opposes the machine's movement": "",
  "The energy lost as heat inside the simple machine": "",
  "Effort force (or input force) is the force you apply to operate a simple machine. For a lever, it is the force you push or pull with. The machine then applies a different force to the load.": "",
  "What does 'load' mean in the context of simple machines?": "",
  "The object or resistance the machine is working against": "",
  "The force applied by the person operating the machine": "",
  "The pivot point around which the machine rotates": "",
  "The material the machine itself is constructed from": "",
  "The load (or resistance force) is the object or force that the simple machine is working against. It is the weight being lifted, the material being cut, or the object being moved.": "",
  "What does 'mechanical advantage' mean?": "",
  "How much a machine multiplies the input force applied": "",
  "The speed at which a machine completes its full task": "",
  "The total amount of energy a machine needs to run": "",
  "The weight of the machine itself in kilograms total": "",
  "Mechanical advantage is the ratio of output force to input force. It tells you how much the machine multiplies your force. A mechanical advantage of 3 means the machine triples your input force.": "",
  "A ramp is used to load a 500 N box onto a truck 1 m high. The ramp is 5 m long. Ideally, how much force is needed to push the box up the ramp?": "",
  "500 newtons of force to push up": "",
  "100 newtons of force to push up": "",
  "2500 newtons of force to push up": "",
  "50 newtons of force to push up": "",
  "Ideally (no friction), work in = work out. Force x distance = weight x height. F x 5 = 500 x 1. F = 100 N. The ramp reduces the force from 500 N to 100 N by increasing the distance.": "",
  "A single fixed pulley is used to lift a 200 N weight. How much force must you pull with (ignoring friction)?": "",
  "200 N of force on the rope end": "",
  "100 N of force on the rope end": "",
  "400 N of force on the rope end": "",
  "50 N of force on the rope end": "",
  "A single fixed pulley only changes the direction of force, not the amount. You still need to pull with 200 N, but you can pull downward instead of lifting upward, which is more convenient.": "",
  "A crowbar is used to pry open a crate. What type of simple machine is being used?": "",
  "A pulley to redirect the force": "",
  "An inclined plane for sliding up": "",
  "A wedge for splitting materials apart": "",
  "A lever to multiply the applied force": "",
  "A crowbar is a lever. The edge of the crate acts as the fulcrum. By pushing down on the long end, you multiply the force at the short end, prying the crate open with much more force than you apply.": "",
  "Why is it easier to push a heavy box up a long, gentle ramp than a short, steep one?": "",
  "The longer ramp requires less force over a greater distance": "",
  "The longer ramp reduces the weight of the heavy box overall": "",
  "The shorter ramp actually requires less total force to push": "",
  "The longer ramp eliminates friction between box and surface": "",
  "A longer, gentler ramp has a greater mechanical advantage. You apply less force over a longer distance. The total work is the same, but the reduced force makes the task manageable.": "",
  "A flagpole uses a pulley system. What advantage does this provide?": "",
  "You can raise the flag by pulling the rope downward": "",
  "The flag becomes lighter when attached to the pulley": "",
  "The pulley creates energy to lift the flag upward": "",
  "The pulley eliminates gravity on the flag completely": "",
  "The flagpole pulley changes the direction of force. Instead of climbing up to push the flag up, you pull the rope down from the ground, and the pulley redirects this force upward to raise the flag.": "",
  "A jar lid is hard to open. What simple machine principle makes it work?": "",
  "The lid works as a screw: an inclined plane wrapped in a spiral": "",
  "The lid works as a lever: a bar rotating around a fulcrum point": "",
  "The lid works as a pulley: a wheel redirecting the applied force": "",
  "The lid works as a wedge: splitting the jar from the lid top": "",
  "A jar lid has spiral threads, making it a screw. The threads are an inclined plane wrapped around the lid. Turning the lid converts rotational motion into linear motion, sealing or opening the jar.": "",
  "An axe splits a log. What two simple machines are combined in the axe?": "",
  "A pulley attached to an inclined plane": "",
  "A wedge (blade) on a lever (handle)": "",
  "A screw connected to a wheel and axle": "",
  "Two inclined planes and one pulley system": "",
  "An axe combines a wedge (the V-shaped blade that splits wood) with a lever (the handle that multiplies force). Many tools are compound machines combining multiple simple machines.": "",
  "A wheelchair ramp at a building entrance is 10 m long and rises 0.5 m. What is the ideal mechanical advantage?": "",
  "5 times force multiplication": "",
  "10 times force multiplication": "",
  "20 times force multiplication": "",
  "0.05 times force multiplication": "",
  "For an inclined plane, ideal mechanical advantage = length / height = 10 m / 0.5 m = 20. The ramp multiplies force by 20, meaning you need only 1/20 of the weight to push up the ramp.": "",
  "A person uses a screwdriver to tighten a screw. What simple machine principles are at work?": "",
  "Only the screw principle is at work here": "",
  "Wheel and axle (handle) and screw (threads) work together": "",
  "Only the lever principle is at work in this case": "",
  "Only the wedge principle is at work for this task": "",
  "A screwdriver combines wheel and axle (the handle is the wheel, the shaft is the axle) with a screw (the fastener's threads). The handle multiplies force, and the screw threads convert rotation to linear clamping force.": "",
  "A construction worker uses a block and tackle (multiple pulleys) to lift a 1000 N beam. With 4 supporting rope sections, what force is needed?": "",
  "250 N of force to lift the beam up": "",
  "1000 N of force to lift the beam up": "",
  "4000 N of force to lift the beam up": "",
  "500 N of force to lift the beam up": "",
  "With 4 supporting rope sections, the mechanical advantage is 4. Force = load / MA = 1000 N / 4 = 250 N. You pull with only 250 N, but you must pull 4 times as much rope.": ""
}